==Chinese==
{{zh-forms|alt=丣}}

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{liushu|p}} – a wine vessel with a pointed bottom.

This is the original character for {{zh-l|酒|alcohol}}. 

Compare {{zh-l|酋}} (the vessel with added strokes indicating long-fermented alcohol or decoration) and {{zh-l|尊}} (two hands holding the vessel).

Visually similar to but etymologically unrelated to {{zh-l|西}} (which originally depicted a bird's nest).

===Etymology===
;"wine; wine vessel"
: From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*jəw||liquor}} (STEDT); cognate with {{och-l|酒|wine}}.

; "''tenth earthly branch''"
: {{zh-ref|Smith (2011)}} suggests that this branch denoted the "waxing half-moon", "construed as a vessel filling with liquid". Noting {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}}'s observation that {{zh-l|酉}}'s OC pronunciation started with *''r-'', Smith reconstructs *''r-juʔ'' which would later lost its archaic pre-initial *''r-'', the same phonological split seen in pairs like {{och-l|游|tr=}} ~ {{och-l|遊|tr=*ju|to flow, to roam}} > ''yóu'' vs. {{och-l|流|tr=*r-ju|flow}} > ''liú''. Smith further supposes that *''r-juʔ'', is an endoactive derivative of *''r-ju'' "flow" by the suffix *-ʔ, meaning "the flowing stage".
: As for {{zh-l|酉}}'s association with the chicken, {{zh-ref|Norman (1985)}} proposes that Chinese and Thai forms derived from Viet-Muong *''rə̆k'' ~ *''ruk'', truncated from {{cog|mkh-vie-pro|*r-kaː||chicken}}, yet {{zh-ref|Ferlus (2013)}} thinks this correspondence unlikely. Possibly, {{zh-l|酉}} was arbitrarily associated with the chicken, just like {{zh-l|辰}} with the dragon.

;“unitary”
:From {{bor|zh|en|unitary|'''u'''nitary}}.

